w Zealand|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in New Zealand| ]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|New Zealand]]\n[[Category:February 2020 events in New Zealand|Coronavirus]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Oceania|New Zealand]]\n[[Category:2020 in New Zealand|Coronavirus]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in New Zealand]]\n", "name_user": "Nixinova", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eStatistics:fix ref", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_New_Zealand"}
{"title_page": "Joe Biden sexual assault allegation", "text_new": "{{short description|Allegation by Tara Reade in March 2020}}\n{{Redirect|Tara Reade|the actress|Tara Reid}}\n{{Use American English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\nIn March 2020, '''Tara Reade''', a former Senate staff assistant of [[Joe Biden]], alleged in an interview that Biden sexually assaulted her in a [[Capitol Hill]] office building in 1993.<ref name=InterceptTimesup>{{cite news|url=https://theintercept.com/2020/03/24/joe-biden-metoo-times-up/|first=Ryan|last=Grim|title=Time's Up Said It Could Not Fund a #MeToo Allegation Against Joe Biden, Citing Its Nonprofit Status and His Presidential Run|website=[[The Intercept]]|date=March 24, 2020 |access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref name=vox>{{cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/3/27/21195935/joe-biden-sexual-assault-allegation|last=North|first=Anna|title=A sexual assault allegation against Joe Biden has ignited a firestorm of controversy|website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|date=March 27, 2020 |access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://thehill.com/hilltv/rising/489719-tara-reade-discusses-biden-allegation-with-hilltvs-rising|title=Tara Reade discusses Biden allegation with Hill.TV's 'Rising'|newspaper=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|date=March 26, 2020 |access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/rose-mcgowan-alyssa-milano-joe-biden-alexandra-tara-reade-kavanaugh-a9454256.html|last=White|first=Adam|title=Rose McGowan calls Charmed co-star Alyssa Milano 'a fraud' for endorsing Joe Biden|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=April 8, 2020 <!-- From the timestamp in the HTML source --> |access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Halper|first=Katie|url=https://www.currentaffairs.org/2020/03/tara-reade-tells-her-story|title=Tara Reade Tells Her Story|date=March 31, 2020|magazine=[[Current Affairs (magazine)|Current Affairs]]|access-date=April 9, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A Biden spokesperson said that the allegation was false.<ref name=\"nyt\">{{Cite news |last=Lerer |first=Lisa |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/12/us/politics/joe-biden-tara-reade-sexual-assault-complaint.html |title=Examining Tara Reade's Sexual Assault Allegation Against Joe Biden |date=April 12, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=April 12, 2020 |last2=Ember |first2=Sydney}}</ref> \n\n''[[The New York Times]]'' reported about the allegation after several smaller publications broke stories, reporting that \"[n]o other allegation about sexual assault surfaced in the course of reporting, nor did any former Biden staff members corroborate any details of Ms. Reade\u2019s allegation. The Times found no pattern of sexual misconduct by Mr. Biden\".<ref name=\"nyt\" /> The handling of the reporting by the media has been criticized by various commentators.\n\n== Background ==\n=== Tara Reade ===\n[[File:SenareaidIDTaraReade.webp|thumb|Tara Reade's U.S. Senate identification badge photo]]\nAt age 29, Tara Reade was a staff assistant in the office of then Senator Joe Biden from  December 1992 to August 1993, with responsibilities such as supervision of the office's [[page of the United States Senate|intern]]s and [[internal mail|mail delivery]].<ref name=\"CA200331\">{{cite web |author1=Katie Halper |title=Tara Reade Tells Her Story |url=https://www.currentaffairs.org/2020/03/tara-reade-tells-her-story |website=Current Affairs |accessdate=18 April 2020 |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAlso known as Alexandra Tara Reade,<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theunion.com/opinion/columns/alexandra-tara-reade-a-girl-walks-into-the-senate/|title=Alexandra Tara Reade: A girl walks into the Senate|last=Reade|first=Alexandra Tara|website=www.theunion.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.salon.com/2020/03/31/a-woman-accuses-joe-biden-of-sexual-assault-and-all-hell-breaks-loose-online-heres-what-we-know/|title=A woman accuses Joe Biden of sexual assault, and all hell breaks loose online. Here's what we know|last=Marcotte|first=Amanda|date=March 31, 2020|website=Salon|language=en|url-status=live|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> she is a writer<ref>https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2020/04/17/joe-biden-tara-reade-metoo-problem-sexual-assault-allegation-column/5140707002/</ref><ref>https://heavy.com/news/2020/03/tara-reade/</ref> from [[Nevada County, California]]<ref name=\"auto1\"/> who has offered her services as a \"[[non-profit organization|non-profit]] [[business consultant|consultant]]\" as of early 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404045216/https://www.alexandrareade.com/|title=Alexandra Tara Reade - Home|date=April 4, 2019|website=web.archive.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alexandrareade.com/|archiveurl=http://archive.today/20190404111507/https://www.alexandrareade.com/|deadurl=y|title=Alexandra Tara Reade - Home}}</ref>{{Primary inline|date=April 2020}}  According to the ''[[Washington Examiner]],'' after working in Washington, Reade left and became a mother, but changed her name multiple times after leaving an abusive marriage.<ref name=\"WE200415\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/everything-we-know-about-the-biden-sexual-assault-allegation|title=Everything we know about the Biden sexual assault allegation|last1=Larsen|first1=Emily|date=April 15, 2020|publisher=Washington Examiner|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref> She earned a law degree from [[Seattle University School of Law]], but has not practiced law and said that she helps nonprofits.<ref name=\"CA200331\" /><ref name=\"WE200415\" /> She has worked as a [[victims rights]] advocate and recently has worked with families who have special needs children.<ref name=\"WE200415\" />  She stated that she is an [[expert witness]] in [[Monterey County, California]] [[domestic violence]] cases, which she does for a stipend.<ref name=\"WE200415\" /><ref name=\"CA200331\" /> She was an actress and a model in her early life.<ref name=\"WE200415\" />\n\n=== Joe Biden ===\n{{Main|Joe Biden}}\nFormer U.S. Vice President Joe Biden served as a U.S. Senator from 1973 to 2009. He has been accused of inappropriate physical contact in the past. Photographs and videos show Biden in close proximity to women and children, including kissing, gripping, [[Eskimo kissing|nose rubbing]] and touching.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2019/3/29/18241598/joe-biden-lucy-flores-touching-women-media-history-explained |accessdate=December 30, 2019 |title=Lucy Flores isn't alone. Joe Biden's got a long history of touching women inappropriately.|last=McGann|first=Laura|date=March 29, 2019|website=Vox}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/joe-biden-2020-harvey-weinstein_n_5a0a0ba8e4b00a6eece3a13e |title=Joe Biden 2020 Is A Terrible Idea In A Post-Weinstein America |last=Terkel |first=Amanda |date=November 15, 2017 |website=HuffPost |access-date=December 30, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://time.com/3713264/joe-biden-stephanie-carter-shoulder-rub/ |title=America Shouldn't Tolerate 'Biden Being Biden' |last=Markowitz |first=Karol |date=February 18, 2015 |website=Time |accessdate=December 30, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"NBCNewYork\">{{cite web |title=Biden Charms Photographers, Frightens Children at Final Swearing-In as VP |url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/national-international/joe-biden-final-congressional-swearing-in-as-vp/2083691/ |website=NBCNewYork |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> Biden has described himself as a \"tactile politician\" and admitted this behavior has caused trouble for him in the past.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/la-na-pol-joe-biden-kiss-lucy-flores-20190329-story.html|title=Nevada Democrat accuses Joe Biden of touching and kissing her without consent at 2014 event |accessdate=December 30, 2019 |last=Brice-Saddler |first=Michael |date=March 29, 2019 |website=Los Angeles Times }}</ref> According to CNN, the women felt uncomfortable but none of them have accused Biden of sexual assault.<ref name=Lee-200417>{{cite news | url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/17/politics/joe-biden-allegations/index.html | title=Democrats grapple with questions about Tara Reade's sexual assault allegation against Joe Biden | work=[[CNN]] | date=April 17, 2020 | accessdate=April 17, 2020 | first=MJ | last=Lee}}</ref>\n\n== Allegations ==\nDuring an interview with a reporter in April 2019, Reade alleged that Biden touched her inappropriately and sexually harassed her while she worked in his U.S. Senate office. Reade made the allegation after watching an episode of the ''[[The View (talk show)|The View]]'' on April 1, 2019, in which Nevada politician [[Lucy Flores]] had alleged that Biden sniffed her hair and kissed the back of her head shortly before a political rally in 2014.<ref name=InterceptTimesup /><ref>{{Cite news|first=Alan|last=Riquelmy|authorlink=|title=Nevada County woman says Joe Biden inappropriately touched her while working in his U.S. Senate office|newspaper=[[The Union (newspaper)|The Union]]|date=April 3, 2019|url=https://www.theunion.com/news/nevada-county-woman-says-joe-biden-inappropriately-touched-her-while-working-in-his-u-s-senate-office/ |access-date=April 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring an interview with Katie Halper which was released as a podcast on March 25, 2020, Reade alleged that Biden had pushed her against a wall and penetrated her with his fingers in a Capitol Hill office building in 1993.<ref name=\"auto\"/> Addressed her objective was for revealing her allegation, Read said during the interview, \"I\u2019m hoping by coming forward with this\u2014and I know it\u2019s hard to listen to, and it\u2019s hard to live in it, right? But my justice now, the only justice I can have, is to be moving freely in the world and to heal and not be silenced.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.currentaffairs.org/2020/03/tara-reade-tells-her-story|title=Tara Reade Tells Her Story \u2767 Current Affairs|first=Current|last=Affairs|website=Current Affairs}}</ref> On April 9, 2020, she filed a police report with the Washington, D.C. police alleging she was sexually assaulted between March 1 and May 31, 1993.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Vitali|first1=Ali|last2=Memoli|first2=Mike|title=Woman broadens claims against Biden to include sexual assault|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/woman-broadens-claims-against-biden-include-sexual-assault-n1182296 |access-date=April 16, 2020|work=NBC News|date=April 12, 2020}}</ref> NPR confirmed that a record of the police report named Biden.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Khalid |first1=Asma |title=On The Record: A Former Biden Staffer's Sexual Assault Allegation |url=https://www.npr.org/2020/04/19/837966525/on-the-record-a-former-biden-staffers-sexual-assault-allegation |accessdate=19 April 2020 |work=NPR |date=19 April 2020}}</ref> Reade acknowledged that the statute of limitations has lapsed, and she stated that she filed the report \"for safety reasons only\".<ref name=vox /><ref name=\"nyt\" /><ref name=Mangan-200414>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/14/joe-biden-accused-of-sex-assault-amid-challenge-to-donald-trump.html|title=Joe Biden is accused of sexual assault as he heads toward election fight with Trump|work=[[CNBC]]|date=April 14, 2020 | access-date=April 15, 2020|first=Dan|last=Mangan}}</ref>\n\nOn April 12, 2020, ''The New York Times'' released an analysis of their investigative reporting in which they interviewed Reade, several of her friends, lawyers, nearly two dozen people who worked with Biden in the early 1990s, and the seven women who accused Biden of kissing, hugging, or touching them in ways that had made them feel uncomfortable. No other allegations about sexual assault surfaced in the course of this reporting, nor did any former Biden staff members corroborate any details of Reade's allegation, although several of the seven women stated that they believed Reade but had no new knowledge of the incident.<ref name=\"nyt\" /> Two friends of Reade confirmed to ''The New York Times'' that she had told them of the alleged assault (one in 1993 shortly after the alleged assault took place, the other in 2008). Reade's brother, Collin Moulton, has also publicly stated that she had told him about it,<ref name=\"nyt\" /> initially saying that Reade told him that Biden had touched her neck and shoulders, but several days later he told ''The Washington Post'' that he also remembered that she had said that Biden had reached \"under her clothes.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ruth|first1=Marcus|title=Assessing Tara Reade's allegations|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/04/15/seriousness-flaws-tara-reades-allegations/|website=The Washington Post |access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n''The New York Times'' reporters additionally interviewed the chief and deputy-chief of Biden's Senate staff during 1992 and 1993 as well as its long-term executive assistant. They expressed their doubts as to the veracity of Reade's account, arguing that that they would have recalled Reade's complaints about Biden's conduct had she made them while also asserting that the behavior alleged would be out of character for him. Melissa Lefko, then a staff assistant for Biden, told the reporters that she had never experienced harassment and that in her opinion, Biden's office was a \"very supportive environment for women.\"<ref name=\"nyt\" />\n\nA '''second accuser''' came forward in an anonymous online ''Theology Corner'' article on April 18, 2020, alleging that Biden had sexually assaulted them previously.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Anonymous|first1=Anonymous|title=Do I have to vote for a rapist if I live in a swing state |url=https://theologycorner.net/blog/uncategorized/do-i-have-to-vote-for-a-rapist-if-i-live-in-a-swing-state/|website=Theology Corner |access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref> This particular allegation remains uncorroborated.  \n\n== Media coverage ==\nThe allegations, and the delayed response by major media publications, stirred mixed sentiments across the American political spectrum.<ref name=Walsh-200415>{{cite news|url=https://www.thenation.com/article/politics/tara-reade-joe-biden-democrats/|title=The Troublesome Tara Reade Story|work=[[The Nation]]|date=April 15, 2020 | access-date=April 16, 2020|first=Joan|last=Walsh}}</ref> On March 28, 2020, ''The Guardian'' columnist Arwa Mahdawi asked in an op-ed: \"Why has the media ignored sexual assault allegations against Biden?\". She also wrote about how right-wing media outlets embraced the controversy, remarking that \"It is hugely frustrating to see conservatives, who couldn't give a damn about the multiple sexual assault allegations against Donald Trump, weaponize the accusations against Biden.\" She added that she found it \"also frustrating to see so many liberals turning a blind eye\" to a serious allegation.<ref name=\"TheWeek-200416\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theweek.co.uk/106651/joe-biden-the-sexual-assault-claim-dividing-democrats|title=Joe Biden: the sexual assault claim dividing Democrats|date=April 16, 2020|work=[[The Week]]|access-date=April 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Mahdawi-200328>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/28/joe-biden-sexual-assault-allegations-why-has-media-ignored-claims|title=Why has the media ignored sexual assault and misbehaviour allegations against Biden?|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=March 28, 2020 | access-date=April 16, 2020|first=Arwa|last=Mahdawi}}</ref>\n\n''The New York Times'' was criticized by other media outlets for its delayed coverage of the allegation, and how it differed from reporting on other allegations in the past.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jacobinmag.com/2020/04/joe-biden-tara-reade-sexual-assault-allegation-media|title=The Media Had a Formula for Reporting Sexual Misconduct. Then Joe Biden Was Accused.|last=Marcetic|first=Branko|date=April 14, 2020|website=Jacobin Magazine|url-status=live|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2020/04/media-floodgates-open-joe-biden-tara-reade-allegation|title=The Media Floodgates Finally Open on Biden Sexual Assault Allegation|last=Ecarma|first=Caleb|date=April 14, 2020|website=Vanity Fair|url-status=live|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/04/joe-biden-harassment-nytimes.html|title=Joe Biden Sails Under the New York Times' Bar for Sexual Abuse|last=Cauterucci|first=Christina|date=April 13, 2020|website=Slate|url-status=live|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref> Its executive editor, [[Dean Baquet]], published an [[op-ed]] on April 13, 2020 responding to various criticisms including that his newspaper was slow to publish coverage of the news story.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2020/04/the-new-york-times-denies-tara-reade-the-christine-blasey-ford-treatment/|title=The New York Times Denies Tara Reade the Christine Blasey Ford Treatment|date=April 14, 2020|website=National Review|language=en-US|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/04/joe-biden-harassment-nytimes.html|title=Joe Biden Sails Under the New York Times' Bar for Sexual Abuse|last=Cauterucci|first=Christina|date=April 13, 2020|website=Slate Magazine|language=en|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2020/04/media-floodgates-open-joe-biden-tara-reade-allegation|title=The Media Floodgates Finally Open on Biden Sexual Assault Allegation|last=Ecarma|first=Caleb|website=Vanity Fair|language=en|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Smith|first=Ben|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/13/business/media/joe-biden-tara-reade-new-york-times.html|title=The Times Took 19 Days to Report an Accusation Against Biden. Here's Why.|date=April 13, 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 15, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In an interview with the newspaper's media columnist [[Ben Smith (journalist)|Ben Smith]], Baquet responded to a controversy about a line in the news story that was removed after the piece's initial publication. The sentence previously read: \"The Times found no pattern of sexual misconduct by Mr. Biden, beyond the hugs, kisses and touching that women previously said made them uncomfortable.\" Baquet explained that it had been included originally in order not to falsely imply that other individuals had made allegations of as invasive in nature as Reade's but thereafter removed because of \"awkward phrasing issue that could be read different ways.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/media/492680-ny-times-faces-blowback-for-removal-of-controversial-passage-on-biden-sexual|title=NY Times faces blowback for removal of controversial passage on Biden sexual assault allegation|last=Swanson|first=Ian|date=April 14, 2020|website=The Hill|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> Baquet stated that the edit was made after [[Joe Biden 2020 presidential campaign|the Biden campaign]] had objected to it because \"[it] made it look like there were other instances in which he had been accused of sexual misconduct.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Reactions ==\nOn April 14, 2020, in an online conversation with [[The Wing (workspace)|The Wing]], [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] [[Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez]] said that it was legitimate to discuss Reade's allegation against Biden.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/alexandria-ocasio-cortez-joe-biden-its-legitimate-to-talk-about-allegations/|title=Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez: \"It's legitimate to talk about\" allegations against Joe Biden|website=www.cbsnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/alexandria-ocasio-cortez-sexual-assault-allegation-joe-biden-news-a9466051.html|title=AOC says it's 'legitimate to talk about' sexual assault allegation against Joe Biden|date=April 15, 2020|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> Other prominent national politicians who have commented on the allegations include Senators [[Bernie Sanders]] and [[Amy Klobuchar]].\n\nMichigan Governor [[Gretchen Whitmer]], a national co-chair of Biden's campaign, discussed the allegation on [[NPR]]. She said \"Well, I think women should be able to tell their stories. I think that it is important that these allegations are vetted, from the media to beyond...And so it's hard to give you greater insight than that, not knowing more about the situation.\"<ref name=mjlee>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/17/politics/joe-biden-allegations/index.html|title=Democrats grapple with questions about Tara Reade's sexual assault allegation against Joe Biden|date=April 17, 2020|first=MJ|last=Lee|website=CNN|language=en|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External link ==\n*{{Cite web|first=Katie|last=Halper|authorlink=|title=Biden accuser: \"I wanted to be a senator; I didn't want to sleep with one\" (audio)|website=Katie Halper podcast|date=March 30, 2020|url=https://soundcloud.com/katie-halper/tara-to-post|access-date=}}\n{{Joe Biden}}\n\n[[Category:2020 controversies in the United States]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:Sexual assaults in the United States]]\n[[Category:Sexual misconduct allegations]]\n[[Category:Media-related controversies in the United States]]\n[[Category:Joe Biden 2020 presidential campaign|Assault allegation]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Allegation by Tara Reade in March 2020}}\n{{Redirect|Tara Reade|the actress|Tara Reid}}\n{{Use American English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\nIn March 2020, '''Tara Reade''', a former Senate staff assistant of [[Joe Biden]], alleged in an interview that Biden sexually assaulted her in a [[Capitol Hill]] office building in 1993.<ref name=InterceptTimesup>{{cite news|url=https://theintercept.com/2020/03/24/joe-biden-metoo-times-up/|first=Ryan|last=Grim|title=Time's Up Said It Could Not Fund a #MeToo Allegation Against Joe Biden, Citing Its Nonprofit Status and His Presidential Run|website=[[The Intercept]]|date=March 24, 2020 |access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref name=vox>{{cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/3/27/21195935/joe-biden-sexual-assault-allegation|last=North|first=Anna|title=A sexual assault allegation against Joe Biden has ignited a firestorm of controversy|website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|date=March 27, 2020 |access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://thehill.com/hilltv/rising/489719-tara-reade-discusses-biden-allegation-with-hilltvs-rising|title=Tara Reade discusses Biden allegation with Hill.TV's 'Rising'|newspaper=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|date=March 26, 2020 |access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/rose-mcgowan-alyssa-milano-joe-biden-alexandra-tara-reade-kavanaugh-a9454256.html|last=White|first=Adam|title=Rose McGowan calls Charmed co-star Alyssa Milano 'a fraud' for endorsing Joe Biden|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=April 8, 2020 <!-- From the timestamp in the HTML source --> |access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Halper|first=Katie|url=https://www.currentaffairs.org/2020/03/tara-reade-tells-her-story|title=Tara Reade Tells Her Story|date=March 31, 2020|magazine=[[Current Affairs (magazine)|Current Affairs]]|access-date=April 9, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A Biden spokesperson said that the allegation was false.<ref name=\"nyt\">{{Cite news |last=Lerer |first=Lisa |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/12/us/politics/joe-biden-tara-reade-sexual-assault-complaint.html |title=Examining Tara Reade's Sexual Assault Allegation Against Joe Biden |date=April 12, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=April 12, 2020 |last2=Ember |first2=Sydney}}</ref> \n\n''[[The New York Times]]'' reported about the allegation after several smaller publications broke stories, reporting that \"[n]o other allegation about sexual assault surfaced in the course of reporting, nor did any former Biden staff members corroborate any details of Ms. Reade\u2019s allegation. The Times found no pattern of sexual misconduct by Mr. Biden\".<ref name=\"nyt\" /> The handling of the reporting by the media has been criticized by various commentators.\n\n== Background ==\n=== Tara Reade ===\n[[File:SenareaidIDTaraReade.webp|thumb|Tara Reade's U.S. Senate identification badge photo]]\nAt age 29, Tara Reade was a staff assistant in the office of then Senator Joe Biden from  December 1992 to August 1993, with responsibilities such as supervision of the office's [[page of the United States Senate|intern]]s and [[internal mail|mail delivery]].<ref name=\"CA200331\">{{cite web |author1=Katie Halper |title=Tara Reade Tells Her Story |url=https://www.currentaffairs.org/2020/03/tara-reade-tells-her-story |website=Current Affairs |accessdate=18 April 2020 |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAlso known as Alexandra Tara Reade,<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theunion.com/opinion/columns/alexandra-tara-reade-a-girl-walks-into-the-senate/|title=Alexandra Tara Reade: A girl walks into the Senate|last=Reade|first=Alexandra Tara|website=www.theunion.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.salon.com/2020/03/31/a-woman-accuses-joe-biden-of-sexual-assault-and-all-hell-breaks-loose-online-heres-what-we-know/|title=A woman accuses Joe Biden of sexual assault, and all hell breaks loose online. Here's what we know|last=Marcotte|first=Amanda|date=March 31, 2020|website=Salon|language=en|url-status=live|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> she is a writer<ref>https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2020/04/17/joe-biden-tara-reade-metoo-problem-sexual-assault-allegation-column/5140707002/</ref><ref>https://heavy.com/news/2020/03/tara-reade/</ref> from [[Nevada County, California]]<ref name=\"auto1\"/> who has offered her services as a \"[[non-profit organization|non-profit]] [[business consultant|consultant]]\" as of early 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404045216/https://www.alexandrareade.com/|title=Alexandra Tara Reade - Home|date=April 4, 2019|website=web.archive.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alexandrareade.com/|archiveurl=http://archive.today/20190404111507/https://www.alexandrareade.com/|deadurl=y|title=Alexandra Tara Reade - Home}}</ref>{{Primary inline|date=April 2020}}  According to the ''[[Washington Examiner]],'' after working in Washington, Reade left and became a mother, but changed her name multiple times after leaving an abusive marriage.<ref name=\"WE200415\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/everything-we-know-about-the-biden-sexual-assault-allegation|title=Everything we know about the Biden sexual assault allegation|last1=Larsen|first1=Emily|date=April 15, 2020|publisher=Washington Examiner|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref> She earned a law degree from [[Seattle University School of Law]], but has not practiced law and said that she helps nonprofits.<ref name=\"CA200331\" /><ref name=\"WE200415\" /> She has worked as a [[victims rights]] advocate and recently has worked with families who have special needs children.<ref name=\"WE200415\" />  She stated that she is an [[expert witness]] in [[Monterey County, California]] [[domestic violence]] cases, which she does for a stipend.<ref name=\"WE200415\" /><ref name=\"CA200331\" /> She was an actress and a model in her early life.<ref name=\"WE200415\" />\n\n=== Joe Biden ===\n{{Main|Joe Biden}}\nFormer U.S. Vice President Joe Biden served as a U.S. Senator from 1973 to 2009. He has been accused of inappropriate physical contact in the past. Photographs and videos show Biden in close proximity to women and children, including kissing, gripping, [[Eskimo kissing|nose rubbing]] and touching.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2019/3/29/18241598/joe-biden-lucy-flores-touching-women-media-history-explained |accessdate=December 30, 2019 |title=Lucy Flores isn't alone. Joe Biden's got a long history of touching women inappropriately.|last=McGann|first=Laura|date=March 29, 2019|website=Vox}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/joe-biden-2020-harvey-weinstein_n_5a0a0ba8e4b00a6eece3a13e |title=Joe Biden 2020 Is A Terrible Idea In A Post-Weinstein America |last=Terkel |first=Amanda |date=November 15, 2017 |website=HuffPost |access-date=December 30, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://time.com/3713264/joe-biden-stephanie-carter-shoulder-rub/ |title=America Shouldn't Tolerate 'Biden Being Biden' |last=Markowitz |first=Karol |date=February 18, 2015 |website=Time |accessdate=December 30, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"NBCNewYork\">{{cite web |title=Biden Charms Photographers, Frightens Children at Final Swearing-In as VP |url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/national-international/joe-biden-final-congressional-swearing-in-as-vp/2083691/ |website=NBCNewYork |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> Biden has described himself as a \"tactile politician\" and admitted this behavior has caused trouble for him in the past.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/la-na-pol-joe-biden-kiss-lucy-flores-20190329-story.html|title=Nevada Democrat accuses Joe Biden of touching and kissing her without consent at 2014 event |accessdate=December 30, 2019 |last=Brice-Saddler |first=Michael |date=March 29, 2019 |website=Los Angeles Times }}</ref> According to CNN, the women felt uncomfortable but none of them have accused Biden of sexual assault.<ref name=Lee-200417>{{cite news | url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/17/politics/joe-biden-allegations/index.html | title=Democrats grapple with questions about Tara Reade's sexual assault allegation against Joe Biden | work=[[CNN]] | date=April 17, 2020 | accessdate=April 17, 2020 | first=MJ | last=Lee}}</ref>\n\n== Allegations ==\nDuring an interview with a reporter in April 2019, Reade alleged that Biden touched her inappropriately and sexually harassed her while she worked in his U.S. Senate office. Reade made the allegation after watching an episode of the ''[[The View (talk show)|The View]]'' on April 1, 2019, in which Nevada politician [[Lucy Flores]] had alleged that Biden sniffed her hair and kissed the back of her head shortly before a political rally in 2014.<ref name=InterceptTimesup /><ref>{{Cite news|first=Alan|last=Riquelmy|authorlink=|title=Nevada County woman says Joe Biden inappropriately touched her while working in his U.S. Senate office|newspaper=[[The Union (newspaper)|The Union]]|date=April 3, 2019|url=https://www.theunion.com/news/nevada-county-woman-says-joe-biden-inappropriately-touched-her-while-working-in-his-u-s-senate-office/ |access-date=April 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring an interview with Katie Halper which was released as a podcast on March 25, 2020, Reade alleged that Biden had pushed her against a wall and penetrated her with his fingers in a Capitol Hill office building in 1993.<ref name=\"auto\"/> Addressed her objective was for revealing her allegation, Read said during the interview, \"I\u2019m hoping by coming forward with this\u2014and I know it\u2019s hard to listen to, and it\u2019s hard to live in it, right? But my justice now, the only justice I can have, is to be moving freely in the world and to heal and not be silenced.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.currentaffairs.org/2020/03/tara-reade-tells-her-story|title=Tara Reade Tells Her Story \u2767 Current Affairs|first=Current|last=Affairs|website=Current Affairs}}</ref> On April 9, 2020, she filed a police report with the Washington, D.C. police alleging she was sexually assaulted between March 1 and May 31, 1993.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Vitali|first1=Ali|last2=Memoli|first2=Mike|title=Woman broadens claims against Biden to include sexual assault|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/woman-broadens-claims-against-biden-include-sexual-assault-n1182296 |access-date=April 16, 2020|work=NBC News|date=April 12, 2020}}</ref> NPR confirmed that a record of the police report named Biden.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Khalid |first1=Asma |title=On The Record: A Former Biden Staffer's Sexual Assault Allegation |url=https://www.npr.org/2020/04/19/837966525/on-the-record-a-former-biden-staffers-sexual-assault-allegation |accessdate=19 April 2020 |work=NPR |date=19 April 2020}}</ref> Reade acknowledged that the statute of limitations has lapsed, and she stated that she filed the report \"for safety reasons only\".<ref name=vox /><ref name=\"nyt\" /><ref name=Mangan-200414>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/14/joe-biden-accused-of-sex-assault-amid-challenge-to-donald-trump.html|title=Joe Biden is accused of sexual assault as he heads toward election fight with Trump|work=[[CNBC]]|date=April 14, 2020 | access-date=April 15, 2020|first=Dan|last=Mangan}}</ref>\n\nOn April 12, 2020, ''The New York Times'' released an analysis of their investigative reporting in which they interviewed Reade, several of her friends, lawyers, nearly two dozen people who worked with Biden in the early 1990s, and the seven women who accused Biden of kissing, hugging, or touching them in ways that had made them feel uncomfortable. No other allegations about sexual assault surfaced in the course of this reporting, nor did any former Biden staff members corroborate any details of Reade's allegation, although several of the seven women stated that they believed Reade but had no new knowledge of the incident.<ref name=\"nyt\" /> Two friends of Reade confirmed to ''The New York Times'' that she had told them of the alleged assault (one in 1993 shortly after the alleged assault took place, the other in 2008). Reade's brother, Collin Moulton, has also publicly stated that she had told him about it,<ref name=\"nyt\" /> initially saying that Reade told him that Biden had touched her neck and shoulders, but several days later he told ''The Washington Post'' that he also remembered that she had said that Biden had reached \"under her clothes.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ruth|first1=Marcus|title=Assessing Tara Reade's allegations|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/04/15/seriousness-flaws-tara-reades-allegations/|website=The Washington Post |access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n''The New York Times'' reporters additionally interviewed the chief and deputy-chief of Biden's Senate staff during 1992 and 1993 as well as its long-term executive assistant. They expressed their doubts as to the veracity of Reade's account, arguing that that they would have recalled Reade's complaints about Biden's conduct had she made them while also asserting that the behavior alleged would be out of character for him. Melissa Lefko, then a staff assistant for Biden, told the reporters that she had never experienced harassment and that in her opinion, Biden's office was a \"very supportive environment for women.\"<ref name=\"nyt\" />\n\nA '''second accuser''' came forward in an anonymous online ''Theology Corner'' article on April 18, 2020, alleging that Biden had sexually assaulted them previously.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Anonymous|first1=Anonymous|title=Do I have to vote for a rapist if I live in a swing state |url=https://theologycorner.net/blog/uncategorized/do-i-have-to-vote-for-a-rapist-if-i-live-in-a-swing-state/|website=Theology Corner |access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref> This particular allegation remains uncorroborated.  \n\n== Media coverage ==\nThe allegations, and the delayed response by major media publications, stirred mixed sentiments across the American political spectrum.<ref name=Walsh-200415>{{cite news|url=https://www.thenation.com/article/politics/tara-reade-joe-biden-democrats/|title=The Troublesome Tara Reade Story|work=[[The Nation]]|date=April 15, 2020 | access-date=April 16, 2020|first=Joan|last=Walsh}}</ref> On March 28, 2020, ''The Guardian'' columnist Arwa Mahdawi asked in an op-ed: \"Why has the media ignored sexual assault allegations against Biden?\". She also wrote about how right-wing media outlets embraced the controversy, remarking that \"It is hugely frustrating to see conservatives, who couldn't give a damn about the multiple sexual assault allegations against Donald Trump, weaponize the accusations against Biden.\" She added that she found it \"also frustrating to see so many liberals turning a blind eye\" to a serious allegation.<ref name=\"TheWeek-200416\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theweek.co.uk/106651/joe-biden-the-sexual-assault-claim-dividing-democrats|title=Joe Biden: the sexual assault claim dividing Democrats|date=April 16, 2020|work=[[The Week]]|access-date=April 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Mahdawi-200328>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/28/joe-biden-sexual-assault-allegations-why-has-media-ignored-claims|title=Why has the media ignored sexual assault and misbehaviour allegations against Biden?|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=March 28, 2020 | access-date=April 16, 2020|first=Arwa|last=Mahdawi}}</ref>\n\n''The New York Times'' was criticized by other media outlets for its delayed coverage of the allegation, and how it differed from reporting on other allegations in the past.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jacobinmag.com/2020/04/joe-biden-tara-reade-sexual-assault-allegation-media|title=The Media Had a Formula for Reporting Sexual Misconduct. Then Joe Biden Was Accused.|last=Marcetic|first=Branko|date=April 14, 2020|website=Jacobin Magazine|url-status=live|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2020/04/media-floodgates-open-joe-biden-tara-reade-allegation|title=The Media Floodgates Finally Open on Biden Sexual Assault Allegation|last=Ecarma|first=Caleb|date=April 14, 2020|website=Vanity Fair|url-status=live|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/04/joe-biden-harassment-nytimes.html|title=Joe Biden Sails Under the New York Times' Bar for Sexual Abuse|last=Cauterucci|first=Christina|date=April 13, 2020|website=Slate|url-status=live|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref> Its executive editor, [[Dean Baquet]], published an [[op-ed]] on April 13, 2020 responding to various criticisms including that his newspaper was slow to publish coverage of the news story.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2020/04/the-new-york-times-denies-tara-reade-the-christine-blasey-ford-treatment/|title=The New York Times Denies Tara Reade the Christine Blasey Ford Treatment|date=April 14, 2020|website=National Review|language=en-US|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/04/joe-biden-harassment-nytimes.html|title=Joe Biden Sails Under the New York Times' Bar for Sexual Abuse|last=Cauterucci|first=Christina|date=April 13, 2020|website=Slate Magazine|language=en|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2020/04/media-floodgates-open-joe-biden-tara-reade-allegation|title=The Media Floodgates Finally Open on Biden Sexual Assault Allegation|last=Ecarma|first=Caleb|website=Vanity Fair|language=en|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Smith|first=Ben|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/13/business/media/joe-biden-tara-reade-new-york-times.html|title=The Times Took 19 Days to Report an Accusation Against Biden. Here's Why.|date=April 13, 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 15, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In an interview with the newspaper's media columnist [[Ben Smith (journalist)|Ben Smith]], Baquet responded to a controversy about a line in the news story that was removed after the piece's initial publication. The sentence previously read: \"The Times found no pattern of sexual misconduct by Mr. Biden, beyond the hugs, kisses and touching that women previously said made them uncomfortable.\" Baquet explained that it had been included originally in order not to falsely imply that other individuals had made allegations of as invasive in nature as Reade's but thereafter removed because of \"awkward phrasing issue that could be read different ways.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/media/492680-ny-times-faces-blowback-for-removal-of-controversial-passage-on-biden-sexual|title=NY Times faces blowback for removal of controversial passage on Biden sexual assault allegation|last=Swanson|first=Ian|date=April 14, 2020|website=The Hill|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> Baquet stated that the edit was made after [[Joe Biden 2020 presidential campaign|the Biden campaign]] had objected to it because \"[it] made it look like there were other instances in which he had been accused of sexual misconduct.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Reactions ==\nOn April 14, 2020, in an online conversation with [[The Wing (workspace)|The Wing]], [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] [[Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez]] said that it was legitimate to discuss Reade's allegation against Biden.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/alexandria-ocasio-cortez-joe-biden-its-legitimate-to-talk-about-allegations/|title=Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez: \"It's legitimate to talk about\" allegations against Joe Biden|website=www.cbsnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/alexandria-ocasio-cortez-sexual-assault-allegation-joe-biden-news-a9466051.html|title=AOC says it's 'legitimate to talk about' sexual assault allegation against Joe Biden|date=April 15, 2020|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> \n\nMichigan Governor [[Gretchen Whitmer]], a national co-chair of Biden's campaign, discussed the allegation on [[NPR]]. She said \"Well, I think women should be able to tell their stories. I think that it is important that these allegations are vetted, from the media to beyond...And so it's hard to give you greater insight than that, not knowing more about the situation.\"<ref name=mjlee>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/17/politics/joe-biden-allegations/index.html|title=Democrats grapple with questions about Tara Reade's sexual assault allegation against Joe Biden|date=April 17, 2020|first=MJ|last=Lee|website=CNN|language=en|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External link ==\n*{{Cite web|first=Katie|last=Halper|authorlink=|title=Biden accuser: \"I wanted to be a senator; I didn't want to sleep with one\" (audio)|website=Katie Halper podcast|date=March 30, 2020|url=https://soundcloud.com/katie-halper/tara-to-post|access-date=}}\n{{Joe Biden}}\n\n[[Category:2020 controversies in the United States]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:Sexual assaults in the United States]]\n[[Category:Sexual misconduct allegations]]\n[[Category:Media-related controversies in the United States]]\n[[Category:Joe Biden 2020 presidential campaign|Assault allegation]]\n", "name_user": "Rtrivisonno", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joe_Biden_sexual_assault_allegation"}
{"title_page": "G. Dennis McGuire", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = G. Dennis McGuire\n| image       = G Dennis Mcguire 7.jpg\n| caption     = \n| birth name  = \n| birth_date  = \n| birth_place = \n| residence = \n| nationality = \n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| occupation  = \n| networth    =\n| website     = \n| signature   = \n}}\n\n'''G. Dennis McGuire''' is a pastor, evangelist, and administrator in the [[Church of God (Cleveland, Tennessee)|Church of God]] denomination.  He served two terms as the General Overseer (2004<ref>A Summary of the History of the Church of God 1886 - 2004 by Dr. Larry Hess: http://media4jesus.com/COG_ORDAIND_MINISTER/PDF/OM_02_02_SUM_HIST_1886-2004.pdf {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714064041/http://media4jesus.com/COG_ORDAIND_MINISTER/PDF/OM_02_02_SUM_HIST_1886-2004.pdf |date=2011-07-14 }}</ref> and 2006<ref>Church of God Faith News Network: http://www.faithnews.cc/2008/08/21/summary-of-the-2008-church-of-god-international-general-assembly/ {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706215534/http://www.faithnews.cc/2008/08/21/summary-of-the-2008-church-of-god-international-general-assembly/ |date=2011-07-06 }}</ref>) and has also been First and Second Assistant General Overseer.<ref>A Summary of the History of the Church of God 1886 - 2004 by Dr. Larry Hess: http://media4jesus.com/COG_ORDAIND_MINISTER/PDF/OM_02_02_SUM_HIST_1886-2004.pdf {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714064041/http://media4jesus.com/COG_ORDAIND_MINISTER/PDF/OM_02_02_SUM_HIST_1886-2004.pdf |date=2011-07-14 }}</ref>  The General Overseer is the highest office in the Church of God and has primary responsibility for leading a current membership of over 7 million members spanning 185 countries.<ref>A Brief History of the Church of God: http://churchofgod.org/a-brief-history-of-the-church-of-god {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110411223107/http://churchofgod.org/a-brief-history-of-the-church-of-god |date=2011-04-11 }}</ref>\n\nMcGuire's ministerial background includes a wide variety of pastoral and administrative roles in the Church of God.  He pastored a total of 16 years before being appointed to serve as Church of God State Overseer of Indiana in 1984.  He went on to serve as the State Overseer of Texas (1986\u201388), Western North Carolina (1988\u201390) and Tennessee.  He has also been the Assistant Director of Evangelism and Home Missions (1990\u201392), and the International Director of Military and Multi-Cultural Ministries.<ref>Upsilon Xi Book of History \u2013 Page 64: http://www.upsilonxi.com/UXAA/Book_of_History/2010_UXAA_Book_of_History_1_21_2010.pdf</ref>\n\nMcGuire holds a [[Bachelor of Science|Bachelor of Arts]] from [[Lee University]], Master of Arts from [[Assemblies of God Theological Seminary]], and [[honorary degree|honorary]] [[Doctorate of Divinity]] degree from [http://ncpedia.org/east-coast-bible-college East Coast Bible College].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Church of God School of Ministry > About > The Staff |url=http://www.elearngate.com/DesktopDefault.aspx?tabid=3092 |website=www.elearngate.com |accessdate=2015-09-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930081315/http://www.elearngate.com/DesktopDefault.aspx?tabid=3092 |archivedate=2015-09-30 }}</ref>  In 1994, he was selected as Lee University's Distinguished Alumnus of the Year.<ref>Lee University Website: http://www.leeuniversity.edu/alumni/info/distinguished-alumni/1990s.aspx {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929083908/http://www.leeuniversity.edu/alumni/info/distinguished-alumni/1990s.aspx |date=2011-09-29 }}</ref>  As a student at Lee, he was elected student body president for the 1965\u201366 school year and was one of the early members of Upsilon Xi.  He was honored in 1998 as Upsilon Xi's Alumnus of the Year.<ref>Upsilon Xi Book of History \u2013 Page 64: http://www.upsilonxi.com/UXAA/Book_of_History/2010_UXAA_Book_of_History_1_21_2010.pdf</ref>\n\nHis hometown city of [[Kingsport, Tennessee]] honored him on August 5, 2007, naming it \"Dr. G. Dennis McGuire Day.\" <ref>Church of God Faith News Network: http://www.faithnews.cc/2007/08/07/general-overseer-mcguire-honored-by-hometown/ {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927215411/http://www.faithnews.cc/2007/08/07/general-overseer-mcguire-honored-by-hometown/ |date=2011-09-27 }}</ref>\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McGuire, G. Dennis}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Pentecostals from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Lee University alumni]]\n[[Category:American evangelists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = G. Dennis McGuire\n| image       = G Dennis Mcguire 7.jpg\n| caption     = \n| birth name  = \n| birth_date  = \n| birth_place = \n| residence = \n| nationality = \n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| occupation  = \n| networth    =\n| website     = \n| signature   = \n}}\n\n'''G. Dennis McGuire''' is a pastor, evangelist, and administrator in the [[Church of God (Cleveland, Tennessee)|Church of God]] denomination.  He served two terms as the General Overseer (2004<ref>A Summary of the History of the Church of God 1886 - 2004 by Dr. Larry Hess: http://media4jesus.com/COG_ORDAIND_MINISTER/PDF/OM_02_02_SUM_HIST_1886-2004.pdf {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714064041/http://media4jesus.com/COG_ORDAIND_MINISTER/PDF/OM_02_02_SUM_HIST_1886-2004.pdf |date=2011-07-14 }}</ref> and 2006<ref>Church of God Faith News Network: http://www.faithnews.cc/2008/08/21/summary-of-the-2008-church-of-god-international-general-assembly/ {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706215534/http://www.faithnews.cc/2008/08/21/summary-of-the-2008-church-of-god-international-general-assembly/ |date=2011-07-06 }}</ref>) and has also been First and Second Assistant General Overseer.<ref>A Summary of the History of the Church of God 1886 - 2004 by Dr. Larry Hess: http://media4jesus.com/COG_ORDAIND_MINISTER/PDF/OM_02_02_SUM_HIST_1886-2004.pdf {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714064041/http://media4jesus.com/COG_ORDAIND_MINISTER/PDF/OM_02_02_SUM_HIST_1886-2004.pdf |date=2011-07-14 }}</ref>  The General Overseer is the highest office in the Church of God and has primary responsibility for leading a current membership of over 7 million members spanning 185 countries.<ref>A Brief History of the Church of God: http://churchofgod.org/a-brief-history-of-the-church-of-god {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110411223107/http://churchofgod.org/a-brief-history-of-the-church-of-god |date=2011-04-11 }}</ref>\n\nMcGuire's ministerial background includes a wide variety of pastoral and administrative roles in the Church of God.  He pastored a total of 16 years before being appointed to serve as Church of God State Overseer of Indiana in 1984.  He went on to serve as the State Overseer of Texas (1986\u201388), Western North Carolina (1988\u201390) and Tennessee.  He has also been the Assistant Director of Evangelism and Home Missions (1990\u201392), and the International Director of Military and Multi-Cultural Ministries.<ref>Upsilon Xi Book of History \u2013 Page 64: http://www.upsilonxi.com/UXAA/Book_of_History/2010_UXAA_Book_of_History_1_21_2010.pdf</ref>\n\nMcGuire holds a [[Bachelor of Science|Bachelor of Arts]] from [[Lee University]], Master of Arts from [[Assemblies of God Theological Seminary]], and [[honorary degree|honorary]] [[Doctorate of Divinity]] degree from [http://ncpedia.org/east-coast-bible-college East Coast Bible College].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Church of God School of Ministry > About > The Staff |url=http://www.elearngate.com/DesktopDefault.aspx?tabid=3092 |website=www.elearngate.com |accessdate=2015-09-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930081315/http://www.elearngate.com/DesktopDefault.aspx?tabid=3092 |archivedate=2015-09-30 }}</ref>  In 1994, he was selected as Lee University's Distinguished Alumnus of the Year.<ref>Lee University Website: http://www.leeuniversity.edu/alumni/info/distinguished-alumni/1990s.aspx {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929083908/http://www.leeuniversity.edu/alumni/info/distinguished-alumni/1990s.aspx |date=2011-09-29 }}</ref>  As a student at Lee, he was elected Student Body President for the 1965-66 school year and was one of the early members of Upsilon Xi.  He was honored in 1998 as Upsilon Xi's Alumnus of the Year.<ref>Upsilon Xi Book of History \u2013 Page 64: http://www.upsilonxi.com/UXAA/Book_of_History/2010_UXAA_Book_of_History_1_21_2010.pdf</ref>\n\nHis hometown city of [[Kingsport, Tennessee]] honored him on August 5, 2007, naming it \"Dr. G. Dennis McGuire Day.\" <ref>Church of God Faith News Network: http://www.faithnews.cc/2007/08/07/general-overseer-mcguire-honored-by-hometown/ {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927215411/http://www.faithnews.cc/2007/08/07/general-overseer-mcguire-honored-by-hometown/ |date=2011-09-27 }}</ref>\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McGuire, G. Dennis}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Pentecostals from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Lee University alumni]]\n[[Category:American evangelists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:replaced: Student Body President \u2192 student body president,typo(s) fixed: 1965-66 \u2192 1965\u201366", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G._Dennis_McGuire"}
{"title_page": "Jeff Probst", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image              = Jeff Probst at 2009 Primetime Emmy Awards.jpg\n| caption            = Probst at the 2009 [[Primetime Emmy Awards]]\n| name               = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1961|11|4|mf=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Wichita, Kansas]], United States\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| occupation         = {{hlist|Television presenter|reality TV show host|executive producer}}\n| years_active       = 1996\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{unbulleted list | {{marriage|Shelley Wright|1996|2001|end=divorced}} | {{marriage|Lisa Ann Russell|2011}}}}\n}} kyleah garrett finessed this mans\n'''Jeff Probst''' (born November 4, 1961)<ref name=\"ArchiveInterview\" /> is an American [[game show host]] and an [[executive producer]]. He is best known as the [[Emmy Award]]-winning host of the U.S. version of the [[reality television]] show ''[[Survivor (American TV series)|Survivor]]''. He was also the host of ''[[The Jeff Probst Show]]'', a [[Broadcast syndication|syndicated]] daytime talk show produced by [[CBS Television Distribution]] from September 2012 to May 2013.\n\n==Early life==\nProbst was born at the [[Wesley Medical Center]] in [[Wichita, Kansas]] to Jerry and Barbara Probst, and grew up primarily in [[Bellevue, Washington]].<ref name=\"ArchiveInterview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.emmytvlegends.org/interviews/people/jeff-probst|title=Jeff Probst Interview|work=Archive of American Television|accessdate=March 23, 2014}}</ref> After graduating from [[Newport High School (Bellevue, Washington)|Newport High School]] in 1979, he attended [[Seattle Pacific University]] and worked at [[Boeing]] [[Motion Picture]]/[[Television]] studio as a [[Television producer|producer]] and [[narrator]] of [[marketing]] [[Videotape|videos]].\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Jeff Probst.jpg|thumb|Probst in 2008]]\nIn addition to ''Survivor'', Probst once hosted [[FX (TV channel)|FX]]'s original half-hour show dedicated to answering viewer letters, ''[[Backchat (1995 TV series)|Backchat]]'', along with ''Sound FX'', a music series featuring [[Orlando Jones]] (1996). Probst also hosted the [[VH1]] series ''[[Rock & Roll Jeopardy!]]'' from 1998 to 2001, and was a correspondent for the syndicated program ''[[Access Hollywood]]''. He also wrote and directed the Lionsgate released film, ''[[Finder's Fee]]''. ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine named Probst one of the \"50 Most Beautiful People\" in 2001. He often contributes to ''[[Jeopardy!]]'' by giving ''Survivor'' related clues from the show's venues, has twice appeared on [[List of Jeopardy! tournaments and events#Celebrity Jeopardy!|Celebrity ''Jeopardy!'']], first in 2001 and again in 2003, and made several cameo appearances during the April 1, 2010 episode.\n\nHe was also a frequent guest star on the sketch show ''[[MADtv]]'', guest starring once a season since the show's 9th season.\n\nProbst also hosts \"Celebrity Superfan Roundtable\" for [[Howard Stern]].\n\nHe is the host of ''[[Survivor (American TV series)|Survivor]]'', a globally-syndicated American reality show which he has hosted since its inception in 2000. He has stated that he had worked hard to get a meeting with series creator [[Mark Burnett]], because he believed the show was \"something special.\"  He delivers the series' signature catch-phrase to losing contestants, \"The tribe has spoken. It's time for you to go\", which was included in [[TV Land]]'s \"The 100 Greatest TV Quotes and Catch Phrases\" special in 2006.<ref>The Star Ledger. December 11, 2006.</ref>\n\nProbst made a guest appearance in a 2003 episode of ''[[Space Ghost Coast to Coast]]'' on [[Cartoon Network]]'s [[Adult Swim]].\n\nOn October 20, 2008, ''[[TV Guide]]'' reported that Probst was developing a new reality TV series for [[CBS]] called ''Live For The Moment''<ref>{{cite web|last=Adalian |first=Josef |url=https://www.thewrap.com/ind-column/probst-spills-beans-new-project-11975 |title=www.thewrap.com December 18, 2009 |publisher=Thewrap.com |date=December 18, 2009 |accessdate=May 23, 2011}}</ref> that was to feature people with terminal illnesses being taken on \"the last adventure of their life\" before they die.<ref>[https://www.tvguide.com/News/Jeff-Probst-Creating-27376.aspx Jeff Probst Hopes to \"Inspire\" with New Reality Series]\" ''[[TV Guide]]''. October 20, 2008. Retrieved on October 24, 2008.</ref>. Only the pilot was aired, on January 28, 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/shows/live-for-the-moment/|title=Live for the Moment|last=TV.com|website=TV.com|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref>\n\nOn April 1, 2009, Probst appeared on the [[CBS]] [[reality television]] [[TV special|special]] ''[[I Get That a Lot]]'', in which he worked a cash register.\n\nIn October 2011, he appeared as himself on the [[sitcom]] ''[[How I Met Your Mother]]'', in the episode \"[[The Stinson Missile Crisis]]\".\n\nIn January 2012, Probst was announced as director of his second feature film, coming-of-age story ''[[Kiss Me (2014 film)|Kiss Me]]'', starring [[John Corbett (actor)|John Corbett]] and [[Sarah Bolger]], with production scheduled to begin in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], the following month.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118048463|date=January 11, 2012|title=Jeff Probst Sets Directorial Follow-up|first=Jeff |last=Sneider|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120115000000/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118048463|archivedate=January 15, 2012|accessdate=January 15, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>  \n\nFrom September 10, 2012, Probst hosted  ''[[The Jeff Probst Show]]'', a [[Broadcast syndication|syndicated]] daytime talk show produced by [[CBS Television Distribution]] from September 2012 to May 2013. CBS did not pick up the show for a second season, citing low ratings.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/02/14/showbiz/tv/probst-talk-show-canceled-ew/ | work=CNN | title=Jeff Probst talk show is canceled \u2013 CNN.com | date=February 14, 2013}}</ref> Starting on October 2012, Probst has hosted the recurring [[Adult Swim]] special, \"[[The Greatest Event in Television History]]\", which consists of remakes of 1980s TV show title sequences.\n\nIn February 2013, Probst teamed up with Christopher Tebbetts to release the first of [[Scholastic Corporation|Scholastic]]'s adventure series ''[[Stranded (book series)|Stranded]]''. Stranded is intended for middle school students, grades 4-6. It follows the story of Vanessa, Buzz, Carter, and Jane as they are left on a deserted island and forced to fend for themselves. It started out as a regular vacation but when a storm sets in, the kids are shipwrecked in the middle of the South Pacific without any parents. They must find a way to work together if they are ever to get off the island. ''Stranded'' is the first of the three book series.\n\nIn November 2013 and January 2014, Probst appeared as himself on the sitcom ''[[Two and a Half Men]]'' in two [[Two and a Half Men (season 11)#Episodes|season 11]] episodes, \"Some Kind of Lesbian Zombie\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3293108/reference |title=\"\"Two and a Half Men\" Some Kind of Lesbian Zombie (2013) |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=IMDb |publisher=[[IMDb|IMDb.com, Inc.]] |accessdate=March 6, 2017}}</ref> and \"Baseball. Boobs. Boobs. Baseball.\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3457430/reference |title=\"\"Two and a Half Men\" Baseball. Boobs. Boobs. Baseball. (2014) |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=IMDb |publisher=[[IMDb|IMDb.com, Inc.]] |accessdate=March 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2016, Probst appeared as himself on the sitcom ''[[Life in Pieces]]'', in the episode \"Swim Survivor Zen Talk\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt6241704/reference |title=\"Life in Pieces\" Swim Survivor Zen Talk (2016) |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=IMDb |publisher=[[IMDb|IMDb.com, Inc.]] |accessdate=March 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+TV\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|1999 - 2001\n|Rock & Roll Jeoprady\n|Host\n|29 episodes\n|-\n|2000 - Present\n|Survivor\n|Executive Director, Producer and Host\n|40 seasons\n|-\n|2011\n|How I Met Your Mother\n|Himself\n|1 episode\n|-\n|2012 - 2013\n|The Jeff Probst Show\n|Host\n|170 episodes\n|-\n|2013 - 2014\n|Two and a Half Men\n|Himself\n|2 episodes\n|-\n|2013\n|Survivor: Blood vs Water Preview\n|Host and Executive Producer\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|The (206)\n|Actor\n|Season 2, Episode 12 \n|-\n|2016\n|Life in Pieces\n|Himself\n|Season 2, Episode 7 (Swim Survivor Zen Talk)\n|-\n|2017\n|Family Guy\n|Voice \n|Season 16, Episode 7 (Peter IV)\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Film\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|2014\n|Kiss Me\n|Director, Producer\n|\n|-\n|2001\n|Finder's Fee\n|Director, Writer\n|\n|}\n\n==Personal life==\nProbst was married to his first wife, psychotherapist Shelley Wright, from 1996 to 2001.<ref name=\"people2004\">{{cite news| url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,1007913,00.html| work= People| title=Jeff Probst Admits to Survivor Romance| date= December 15, 2004 | accessdate= September 27, 2013|first=Cynthia|last=Wang}}</ref> In 2004, after filming on ''[[Survivor: Vanuatu]]'' wrapped, he began dating one of the contestants, [[Julie Berry]].<ref name=\"people2004\"/> They broke up in early 2008.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/people/celebwatch/2008-04-27-jeff-probst_N.htm| work= USA Today| title=Celeb Watch: 'Survivor' host Jeff Probst will survive -- and thrive| date= April 27, 2008 | accessdate= September 27, 2013| first=Will| last=Keck}}</ref> Probst married his second wife, Lisa Ann Russell, on December 5, 2011.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20551944,00.html | work= [[People (magazine)|People]] | title=Jeff Probst Weds Lisa Ann Russell| first=Cynthia | last=Wang | date= December 8, 2011 | accessdate= December 9, 2011}}</ref> Through this marriage, Probst is a [[stepfather]] to Russell's two children, son Michael (born in 2004) and daughter Ava (born in 2006), from her former marriage to actor [[Mark-Paul Gosselaar]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,1191724,00.html| work= [[People (magazine)|People]] | title=Mark-Paul Gosselaar, Wife Have a Girl| date= May 7, 2006| accessdate= May 13, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/survivor-host-jeff-probst-marries-lisa-ann-russell-2011812| work= Us Weekly | title=Survivor Host Jeff Probst Marries Lisa Ann Russell!| date= December 8, 2011| accessdate= May 13, 2013}}</ref> Probst has stated that he and his wife amicably share custody with Gosselaar and his second wife, and that the children consider all four to be parents.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://ca.eonline.com/news/371012/survivor-s-jeff-probst-talks-sharing-custody-with-mark-paul-gosselaar-on-larry-king-now| work= E Online | title=Survivor's Jeff Probst Talks Sharing Custody With Mark-Paul Gosselaar on Larry King Now| date= December 12, 2012| accessdate= September 27, 2013|first=Tierney|last=Bricker}}</ref>\n\nProbst keeps the [[Candle snuffer|snuffer]] that he uses to snuff the torches when a contestant is voted out of the game as a [[souvenir]] after every season of ''Survivor''.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/people/celebwatch/2008-04-27-jeff-probst_N.htm | work=USA Today | title=Celeb Watch: 'Survivor' host Jeff Probst will survive -- and thrive; see video | first=Will | last=Keck | date=April 27, 2008 | accessdate=May 6, 2010}}</ref>\nHe has written a book called ''Stranded'', based on the show ''Survivor.'' As an ordained minister, he has presided over the weddings of several of his friends.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rizzo|first1=Monica|last2=Wang|first2=Cynthia|title=Jenna Fischer's Minister at Her Wedding: Jeff Probst|url=http://people.com/celebrity/jenna-fischers-minister-at-her-wedding-jeff-probst/|work=People.com|date=September 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nOn September 21, 2008, Probst won the first [[Primetime Emmy Award]] for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Host for a Reality or Reality-Competition Program|Outstanding Host for a Reality or Reality-Competition Program]]. He won the same award in 2009, 2010, and 2011.  The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' attributed Probst's undefeated track record in the category to his penchant for interacting with contestants on a compassionate personal level unseen in any of his competitors, transcending his role of host to that of counselor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/awards/2011/09/emmy-secret-revealed-why-survivor-host-jeff-probst-is-unbeatable.html|title=Emmy secret revealed: Why 'Survivor' host Jeff Probst is unbeatable|date=September 14, 2011|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb name|0698251}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080202171929/http://www.cbs.com/primetime/survivor16/about/host.php CBS.com profile]\n* {{EmmyTVLegends name|jeff-probst|Jeff Probst}}\n\n{{Survivor|SURVUS}}\n{{Jeopardy!}}\n{{EmmyAward RealityHost}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Television|United States}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Probst, Jeff}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Le Cordon Bleu]]\n[[Category:American game show hosts]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American television talk show hosts]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Bellevue, Washington]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Seattle]]\n[[Category:People from Wichita, Kansas]]\n[[Category:Primetime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Seattle Pacific University alumni]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Kansas]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image              = Jeff Probst at 2009 Primetime Emmy Awards.jpg\n| caption            = Probst at the 2009 [[Primetime Emmy Awards]]\n| name               = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1961|11|4|mf=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Wichita, Kansas]], United States\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| occupation         = {{hlist|Television presenter|reality TV show host|executive producer}}\n| years_active       = 1996\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{unbulleted list | {{marriage|Shelley Wright|1996|2001|end=divorced}} | {{marriage|Lisa Ann Russell|2011}}}}\n}}\n'''Jeff Probst''' (born November 4, 1961)<ref name=\"ArchiveInterview\" /> is an American [[game show host]] and an [[executive producer]]. He is best known as the [[Emmy Award]]-winning host of the U.S. version of the [[reality television]] show ''[[Survivor (American TV series)|Survivor]]''. He was also the host of ''[[The Jeff Probst Show]]'', a [[Broadcast syndication|syndicated]] daytime talk show produced by [[CBS Television Distribution]] from September 2012 to May 2013.\n\n==Early life==\nProbst was born at the [[Wesley Medical Center]] in [[Wichita, Kansas]] to Jerry and Barbara Probst, and grew up primarily in [[Bellevue, Washington]].<ref name=\"ArchiveInterview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.emmytvlegends.org/interviews/people/jeff-probst|title=Jeff Probst Interview|work=Archive of American Television|accessdate=March 23, 2014}}</ref> After graduating from [[Newport High School (Bellevue, Washington)|Newport High School]] in 1979, he attended [[Seattle Pacific University]] and worked at [[Boeing]] [[Motion Picture]]/[[Television]] studio as a [[Television producer|producer]] and [[narrator]] of [[marketing]] [[Videotape|videos]].\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Jeff Probst.jpg|thumb|Probst in 2008]]\nIn addition to ''Survivor'', Probst once hosted [[FX (TV channel)|FX]]'s original half-hour show dedicated to answering viewer letters, ''[[Backchat (1995 TV series)|Backchat]]'', along with ''Sound FX'', a music series featuring [[Orlando Jones]] (1996). Probst also hosted the [[VH1]] series ''[[Rock & Roll Jeopardy!]]'' from 1998 to 2001, and was a correspondent for the syndicated program ''[[Access Hollywood]]''. He also wrote and directed the Lionsgate released film, ''[[Finder's Fee]]''. ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine named Probst one of the \"50 Most Beautiful People\" in 2001. He often contributes to ''[[Jeopardy!]]'' by giving ''Survivor'' related clues from the show's venues, has twice appeared on [[List of Jeopardy! tournaments and events#Celebrity Jeopardy!|Celebrity ''Jeopardy!'']], first in 2001 and again in 2003, and made several cameo appearances during the April 1, 2010 episode.\n\nHe was also a frequent guest star on the sketch show ''[[MADtv]]'', guest starring once a season since the show's 9th season.\n\nProbst also hosts \"Celebrity Superfan Roundtable\" for [[Howard Stern]].\n\nHe is the host of ''[[Survivor (American TV series)|Survivor]]'', a globally-syndicated American reality show which he has hosted since its inception in 2000. He has stated that he had worked hard to get a meeting with series creator [[Mark Burnett]], because he believed the show was \"something special.\"  He delivers the series' signature catch-phrase to losing contestants, \"The tribe has spoken. It's time for you to go\", which was included in [[TV Land]]'s \"The 100 Greatest TV Quotes and Catch Phrases\" special in 2006.<ref>The Star Ledger. December 11, 2006.</ref>\n\nProbst made a guest appearance in a 2003 episode of ''[[Space Ghost Coast to Coast]]'' on [[Cartoon Network]]'s [[Adult Swim]].\n\nOn October 20, 2008, ''[[TV Guide]]'' reported that Probst was developing a new reality TV series for [[CBS]] called ''Live For The Moment''<ref>{{cite web|last=Adalian |first=Josef |url=https://www.thewrap.com/ind-column/probst-spills-beans-new-project-11975 |title=www.thewrap.com December 18, 2009 |publisher=Thewrap.com |date=December 18, 2009 |accessdate=May 23, 2011}}</ref> that was to feature people with terminal illnesses being taken on \"the last adventure of their life\" before they die.<ref>[https://www.tvguide.com/News/Jeff-Probst-Creating-27376.aspx Jeff Probst Hopes to \"Inspire\" with New Reality Series]\" ''[[TV Guide]]''. October 20, 2008. Retrieved on October 24, 2008.</ref>. Only the pilot was aired, on January 28, 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/shows/live-for-the-moment/|title=Live for the Moment|last=TV.com|website=TV.com|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref>\n\nOn April 1, 2009, Probst appeared on the [[CBS]] [[reality television]] [[TV special|special]] ''[[I Get That a Lot]]'', in which he worked a cash register.\n\nIn October 2011, he appeared as himself on the [[sitcom]] ''[[How I Met Your Mother]]'', in the episode \"[[The Stinson Missile Crisis]]\".\n\nIn January 2012, Probst was announced as director of his second feature film, coming-of-age story ''[[Kiss Me (2014 film)|Kiss Me]]'', starring [[John Corbett (actor)|John Corbett]] and [[Sarah Bolger]], with production scheduled to begin in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], the following month.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118048463|date=January 11, 2012|title=Jeff Probst Sets Directorial Follow-up|first=Jeff |last=Sneider|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120115000000/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118048463|archivedate=January 15, 2012|accessdate=January 15, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>  \n\nFrom September 10, 2012, Probst hosted  ''[[The Jeff Probst Show]]'', a [[Broadcast syndication|syndicated]] daytime talk show produced by [[CBS Television Distribution]] from September 2012 to May 2013. CBS did not pick up the show for a second season, citing low ratings.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/02/14/showbiz/tv/probst-talk-show-canceled-ew/ | work=CNN | title=Jeff Probst talk show is canceled \u2013 CNN.com | date=February 14, 2013}}</ref> Starting on October 2012, Probst has hosted the recurring [[Adult Swim]] special, \"[[The Greatest Event in Television History]]\", which consists of remakes of 1980s TV show title sequences.\n\nIn February 2013, Probst teamed up with Christopher Tebbetts to release the first of [[Scholastic Corporation|Scholastic]]'s adventure series ''[[Stranded (book series)|Stranded]]''. Stranded is intended for middle school students, grades 4-6. It follows the story of Vanessa, Buzz, Carter, and Jane as they are left on a deserted island and forced to fend for themselves. It started out as a regular vacation but when a storm sets in, the kids are shipwrecked in the middle of the South Pacific without any parents. They must find a way to work together if they are ever to get off the island. ''Stranded'' is the first of the three book series.\n\nIn November 2013 and January 2014, Probst appeared as himself on the sitcom ''[[Two and a Half Men]]'' in two [[Two and a Half Men (season 11)#Episodes|season 11]] episodes, \"Some Kind of Lesbian Zombie\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3293108/reference |title=\"\"Two and a Half Men\" Some Kind of Lesbian Zombie (2013) |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=IMDb |publisher=[[IMDb|IMDb.com, Inc.]] |accessdate=March 6, 2017}}</ref> and \"Baseball. Boobs. Boobs. Baseball.\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3457430/reference |title=\"\"Two and a Half Men\" Baseball. Boobs. Boobs. Baseball. (2014) |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=IMDb |publisher=[[IMDb|IMDb.com, Inc.]] |accessdate=March 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2016, Probst appeared as himself on the sitcom ''[[Life in Pieces]]'', in the episode \"Swim Survivor Zen Talk\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt6241704/reference |title=\"Life in Pieces\" Swim Survivor Zen Talk (2016) |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=IMDb |publisher=[[IMDb|IMDb.com, Inc.]] |accessdate=March 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+TV\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|1999 - 2001\n|Rock & Roll Jeoprady\n|Host\n|29 episodes\n|-\n|2000 - Present\n|Survivor\n|Executive Director, Producer and Host\n|40 seasons\n|-\n|2011\n|How I Met Your Mother\n|Himself\n|1 episode\n|-\n|2012 - 2013\n|The Jeff Probst Show\n|Host\n|170 episodes\n|-\n|2013 - 2014\n|Two and a Half Men\n|Himself\n|2 episodes\n|-\n|2013\n|Survivor: Blood vs Water Preview\n|Host and Executive Producer\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|The (206)\n|Actor\n|Season 2, Episode 12 \n|-\n|2016\n|Life in Pieces\n|Himself\n|Season 2, Episode 7 (Swim Survivor Zen Talk)\n|-\n|2017\n|Family Guy\n|Voice \n|Season 16, Episode 7 (Peter IV)\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Film\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|2014\n|Kiss Me\n|Director, Producer\n|\n|-\n|2001\n|Finder's Fee\n|Director, Writer\n|\n|}\n\n==Personal life==\nProbst was married to his first wife, psychotherapist Shelley Wright, from 1996 to 2001.<ref name=\"people2004\">{{cite news| url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,1007913,00.html| work= People| title=Jeff Probst Admits to Survivor Romance| date= December 15, 2004 | accessdate= September 27, 2013|first=Cynthia|last=Wang}}</ref> In 2004, after filming on ''[[Survivor: Vanuatu]]'' wrapped, he began dating one of the contestants, [[Julie Berry]].<ref name=\"people2004\"/> They broke up in early 2008.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/people/celebwatch/2008-04-27-jeff-probst_N.htm| work= USA Today| title=Celeb Watch: 'Survivor' host Jeff Probst will survive -- and thrive| date= April 27, 2008 | accessdate= September 27, 2013| first=Will| last=Keck}}</ref> Probst married his second wife, Lisa Ann Russell, on December 5, 2011.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20551944,00.html | work= [[People (magazine)|People]] | title=Jeff Probst Weds Lisa Ann Russell| first=Cynthia | last=Wang | date= December 8, 2011 | accessdate= December 9, 2011}}</ref> Through this marriage, Probst is a [[stepfather]] to Russell's two children, son Michael (born in 2004) and daughter Ava (born in 2006), from her former marriage to actor [[Mark-Paul Gosselaar]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,1191724,00.html| work= [[People (magazine)|People]] | title=Mark-Paul Gosselaar, Wife Have a Girl| date= May 7, 2006| accessdate= May 13, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/survivor-host-jeff-probst-marries-lisa-ann-russell-2011812| work= Us Weekly | title=Survivor Host Jeff Probst Marries Lisa Ann Russell!| date= December 8, 2011| accessdate= May 13, 2013}}</ref> Probst has stated that he and his wife amicably share custody with Gosselaar and his second wife, and that the children consider all four to be parents.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://ca.eonline.com/news/371012/survivor-s-jeff-probst-talks-sharing-custody-with-mark-paul-gosselaar-on-larry-king-now| work= E Online | title=Survivor's Jeff Probst Talks Sharing Custody With Mark-Paul Gosselaar on Larry King Now| date= December 12, 2012| accessdate= September 27, 2013|first=Tierney|last=Bricker}}</ref>\n\nProbst keeps the [[Candle snuffer|snuffer]] that he uses to snuff the torches when a contestant is voted out of the game as a [[souvenir]] after every season of ''Survivor''.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/people/celebwatch/2008-04-27-jeff-probst_N.htm | work=USA Today | title=Celeb Watch: 'Survivor' host Jeff Probst will survive -- and thrive; see video | first=Will | last=Keck | date=April 27, 2008 | accessdate=May 6, 2010}}</ref>\nHe has written a book called ''Stranded'', based on the show ''Survivor.'' As an ordained minister, he has presided over the weddings of several of his friends.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rizzo|first1=Monica|last2=Wang|first2=Cynthia|title=Jenna Fischer's Minister at Her Wedding: Jeff Probst|url=http://people.com/celebrity/jenna-fischers-minister-at-her-wedding-jeff-probst/|work=People.com|date=September 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nOn September 21, 2008, Probst won the first [[Primetime Emmy Award]] for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Host for a Reality or Reality-Competition Program|Outstanding Host for a Reality or Reality-Competition Program]]. He won the same award in 2009, 2010, and 2011.  The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' attributed Probst's undefeated track record in the category to his penchant for interacting with contestants on a compassionate personal level unseen in any of his competitors, transcending his role of host to that of counselor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/awards/2011/09/emmy-secret-revealed-why-survivor-host-jeff-probst-is-unbeatable.html|title=Emmy secret revealed: Why 'Survivor' host Jeff Probst is unbeatable|date=September 14, 2011|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb name|0698251}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080202171929/http://www.cbs.com/primetime/survivor16/about/host.php CBS.com profile]\n* {{EmmyTVLegends name|jeff-probst|Jeff Probst}}\n\n{{Survivor|SURVUS}}\n{{Jeopardy!}}\n{{EmmyAward RealityHost}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Television|United States}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Probst, Jeff}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Le Cordon Bleu]]\n[[Category:American game show hosts]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American television talk show hosts]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Bellevue, Washington]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Seattle]]\n[[Category:People from Wichita, Kansas]]\n[[Category:Primetime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Seattle Pacific University alumni]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Kansas]]\n", "name_user": "71.63.179.193", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeff_Probst"}
